<br>
I've read that Mars at it's closest approach to Earth, is some 35 million miles distant.  So to traverse that distance in 48 hours would require an average speed of about 730,000 mph, discounting acceleration to cruise speed, and deceleration for Mars orbit.  Now, 1G acceleration is a change in speed of 22.374 mph per second, the total number of seconds available in 48 hours (your estimate of 2 days trip time) is 172,800.<br>
<br>
22.374 mph (1g acceleration) x 172,800 (number of seconds in 48 hours) = 3,866,227.2 mph<br>
<br>
So it's technically do-able... although if it had to fire off a pulse every second, that would require 172,800 of them! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 70<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/2/02 11:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=17.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How fast is FAST?</span><hr size=1> I don't know if it would be able to lug around that many pulse units.<br>
