&gt; I've heard the claim of 125 days round trip for a nuclear pulse rocket like Orion (can this be substantiated?)... what about nuclear thermal?<br>
<br>
<a href=http://www.astronautix.com/articles/probirth.htm>Flora</a> wrote:<br>
 Several mission profiles were contemplated; the one developed in greatest detail appears to have been a Mars flight. Eight astronauts, with around 100 tons of equipment and supplies, could have made a round trip to Mars in 125 days (43)<br>
43.        Freeman Dyson, &quot;Death of a Project&quot;, Science (9 July 1965), pp. 141-142.<br>
<br>
From the Penn St <a href=http://www.engr.psu.edu/antimatter/>ACMF</a> article:<br>
&quot; Isp 13,000 sec, Delta-V 100km/sec&quot;<br>
Page 2 has &quot;estimates of component masses for 120 day, Delta-V 100km/sec Mars mission...&quot;<br>
<br>
Page 3 &quot;thrust  is about 100kn, which accelerates the outbound craft to a Delta-V of 25km/sec in 3 days...&quot;<br>
 (Fairly gentle thrust. Less than the Orion 10 meter ship, I suspect. Can anyone convert the thrust given in the OrionSaturn-V graphics we've gotten from astronautix.com to kilo-newtons?)<br>
<br>
page 5 Earth-Mars round trip; 30 day stay, 120 day total<br>
<br>
Note that the ACMF ship still must wait for a window every 2 years. This is about what a chem rocket does, but the chem rocket takes 180+days  _one way_.<br>
Note that both the Orion 10 meter and the ACMF have about 40% cargo mass fraction. For a chem rocket to make a 180day trajectory to Mars, it must strip down not only cargo but essential redundant systems for crew safety to load up with fuel for a piddly 6-7km/s outbound Delta-V.<br>
For a standard minimum energy trajectory of 9 months, an NTR transfer stage gives a Mars trip about 45% more cargo mass fraction than chemical. Strip down to the same cargo as a chemical rocket, and the NTR gives a 6 month one-way trip.<br>
<br>
 No way could even an Orion thrust 10m/s/s all the way. This kind of performance is reserved for the Federation's Starfleet -whenever they show up.<br>
<br>
 Note that in an emergency or if refueling is possible at the dsstination, the NPR could thrust outbound to 50km/s, coast, then brake for 50km/s. I haven't the means to figure out the trip time here... There was a program which lets you play around with trip times &amp; trajectories to Mars, but it couldn't accept inputs for delta-Vs like this! Because this kind of performance is 'way beyond even NTR.<br>
 Not even VASIMR can do this (and VASIMR requires substantial new technical innovations to get off the drawing boards. We've been making reliable atom bombs since 1944-45).<br>
